      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "title: \"Bond Pricing Under Stochastic Interest Rates\"\n",
        "author: \"Financial Risk Management\"\n",
        "date: today\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Introduction\n",
        "\n",
        "Bond pricing under stochastic interest rates is more complex than under constant rates, because the future interest rates that discount the bond's cashflows are themselves uncertain. This section develops the valuation framework and demonstrates how to estimate bond prices using Monte Carlo simulation.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Zero-Coupon Bonds: Fundamental Concepts\n",
        "\n",
        "A **zero-coupon bond** is a bond that pays no coupons and returns only a single payment (face value $F$) at maturity $T$. It is the building block for bond valuation.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Notation\n",
        "\n",
        "| Symbol | Definition | Units |\n",
        "|--------|------------|-------|\n",
        "| $P(t, T)$ | Bond price at time $t$ for maturity $T$ | Currency (\\$) |\n",
        "| $F$ | Face value (principal) | Currency (typically \\$100 or \\$1000) |\n",
        "| $r_s$ | Short-term interest rate at time $s$ | Annual rate (e.g., 0.03 = 3%) |\n",
        "| $T$ | Maturity date | Years |\n",
        "| $t$ | Current time | Years (usually $t = 0$ for today) |\n",
        "| $E_t[\\cdot]$ | Expectation operator | Conditional on time $t$ information |\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Bond Pricing Under Deterministic Rates\n",
        "\n",
        "If interest rates were constant at level $r$, the bond price would be:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$P(0, T) = \\frac{F}{(1+r)^T}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This is straightforward discounting—the face value is discounted back at the constant rate.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Bond Pricing Under Stochastic Rates\n",
        "\n",
        "When rates are stochastic (uncertain), the bond price is the **expected present value** of the terminal payoff, discounted at stochastic rates:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$P(t, T) = E_t \\left[ \\exp\\left( -\\int_t^T r_s \\, ds \\right) \\right]$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Where:\n",
        "- $E_t[\\cdot]$ = Expectation conditional on information at time $t$\n",
        "- $\\int_t^T r_s \\, ds$ = Cumulative interest rate from $t$ to $T$\n",
        "- The exponential of the negative integral is the **stochastic discount factor**\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key Insight**: The bond price is not just the discounted payoff at a single rate, but rather an **average over all possible future interest rate paths**, weighted by their probability.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Closed-Form Solutions for the Dothan Model\n",
        "\n",
        "For the Dothan model, there exists a closed-form solution for zero-coupon bond prices. This is one of the model's attractions.\n",
        "\n",
        "### The Bond Pricing Formula\n",
        "\n",
        "Under the Dothan model with risk-neutral parameters $\\mu^Q$ and volatility $\\sigma$, the zero-coupon bond price is:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$P(t, T) = \\exp\\left\\{ -\\frac{r_t}{\\mu^Q} \\left[ \\exp(\\mu^Q(T-t)) - 1 \\right] \\right\\}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Alternatively, using the original drift $\\mu$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$P(t, T) = \\left( \\frac{r_T}{r_t} \\right)^{-\\lambda} \\cdot \\text{[adjustment for volatility]}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Where $\\lambda$ is related to the market price of interest rate risk.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Practical Observation\n",
        "\n",
        "For numerical work, it's often easier to use **Monte Carlo simulation** rather than memorizing closed forms, especially as models become more complex.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Monte Carlo Bond Pricing\n",
        "\n",
        "### Method 1: Simulation-Based Pricing\n",
        "\n",
        "The bond price can be estimated by:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Simulate** many interest rate paths from time $t$ to time $T$\n",
        "2. **Accumulate** the integral $\\int_t^T r_s \\, ds$ along each path\n",
        "3. **Compute** the discount factor $\\exp(-\\int_t^T r_s ds)$ for each path\n",
        "4. **Average** the discount factors across all paths\n",
        "\n",
        "### Algorithm\n",
        "\n",
        "```\n",
        "Input: Current time t, maturity T, current rate r_t, number of paths M\n",
        "Output: Estimated bond price P(t,T)\n",
        "\n",
        "Initialize: sum_payoffs = 0\n",
        "\n",
        "For each path m = 1 to M:\n",
        "    Simulate the interest rate path from t to T\n",
        "    Integral_m = 0\n",
        "    \n",
        "    For each time step i from t+Δt to T:\n",
        "        rate = r_i (from simulation)\n",
        "        Integral_m += rate * Δt\n",
        "    \n",
        "    Discount_m = exp(-Integral_m)\n",
        "    sum_payoffs += Discount_m\n",
        "\n",
        "Bond_Price = sum_payoffs / M\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "### Code Implementation"
      ],
      "id": "14ea7d5e"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| label: monte-carlo-bond-pricing\n",
        "#| code-fold: false\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "class DothanBondPricer:\n",
        "    \"\"\"Bond pricing under the Dothan model using Monte Carlo\"\"\"\n",
        "    \n",
        "    def __init__(self, r0, mu, sigma):\n",
        "        \"\"\"\n",
        "        Parameters:\n",
        "        -----------\n",
        "        r0 : float\n",
        "            Initial short rate\n",
        "        mu : float\n",
        "            Drift parameter\n",
        "        sigma : float\n",
        "            Volatility parameter\n",
        "        \"\"\"\n",
        "        self.r0 = r0\n",
        "        self.mu = mu\n",
        "        self.sigma = sigma\n",
        "    \n",
        "    def price_bond(self, T, maturity, dt=0.01, n_paths=10000, seed=None):\n",
        "        \"\"\"\n",
        "        Price a zero-coupon bond using Monte Carlo\n",
        "        \n",
        "        Parameters:\n",
        "        -----------\n",
        "        T : float\n",
        "            Current time (typically 0)\n",
        "        maturity : float\n",
        "            Bond maturity (years from now)\n",
        "        dt : float\n",
        "            Time step for discretization\n",
        "        n_paths : int\n",
        "            Number of Monte Carlo paths\n",
        "        seed : int, optional\n",
        "            Random seed\n",
        "        \n",
        "        Returns:\n",
        "        --------\n",
        "        bond_price : float\n",
        "            Estimated bond price\n",
        "        bond_price_std : float\n",
        "            Standard error of estimate\n",
        "        \"\"\"\n",
        "        if seed is not None:\n",
        "            np.random.seed(seed)\n",
        "        \n",
        "        n_steps = int(maturity / dt)\n",
        "        discount_factors = np.zeros(n_paths)\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Simulate paths\n",
        "        for path in range(n_paths):\n",
        "            r = self.r0\n",
        "            cumulative_integral = 0\n",
        "            \n",
        "            for step in range(n_steps):\n",
        "                Z = np.random.standard_normal()\n",
        "                drift = self.mu * r * dt\n",
        "                diffusion = self.sigma * r * np.sqrt(dt) * Z\n",
        "                r = r + drift + diffusion\n",
        "                r = max(r, 1e-6)  # Ensure positive rates\n",
        "                cumulative_integral += r * dt\n",
        "            \n",
        "            discount_factors[path] = np.exp(-cumulative_integral)\n",
        "        \n",
        "        bond_price = np.mean(discount_factors)\n",
        "        bond_price_std = np.std(discount_factors) / np.sqrt(n_paths)\n",
        "        \n",
        "        return bond_price, bond_price_std\n",
        "    \n",
        "    def price_bonds_across_maturities(self, maturities, dt=0.01, n_paths=10000):\n",
        "        \"\"\"\n",
        "        Price bonds for multiple maturities\n",
        "        \n",
        "        Parameters:\n",
        "        -----------\n",
        "        maturities : array-like\n",
        "            Bond maturities in years\n",
        "        dt : float\n",
        "            Time step\n",
        "        n_paths : int\n",
        "            Number of paths\n",
        "        \n",
        "        Returns:\n",
        "        --------\n",
        "        prices : dict\n",
        "            Dictionary with maturity -> price pairs\n",
        "        \"\"\"\n",
        "        prices = {}\n",
        "        for T in maturities:\n",
        "            price, std = self.price_bond(0, T, dt, n_paths, seed=42)\n",
        "            prices[T] = price\n",
        "        \n",
        "        return prices\n",
        "\n",
        "# Example: Price bonds for different maturities\n",
        "pricer = DothanBondPricer(r0=0.03, mu=0.02, sigma=0.15)\n",
        "maturities = np.array([1, 3, 5, 10])\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Bond Prices (Face Value = $1):\")\n",
        "print(\"-\" * 40)\n",
        "prices = {}\n",
        "for T in maturities:\n",
        "    price, std = pricer.price_bond(0, T, dt=0.01, n_paths=5000, seed=42)\n",
        "    prices[T] = price\n",
        "    print(f\"Maturity {T:2d} years: ${price:.4f} (±{std:.4f})\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Visualization\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
        "bond_prices = list(prices.values())\n",
        "ax.plot(maturities, bond_prices, 'o-', linewidth=2.5, markersize=8, color='darkblue')\n",
        "ax.fill_between(maturities, \n",
        "                 np.array(bond_prices) * 0.98,\n",
        "                 np.array(bond_prices) * 1.02,\n",
        "                 alpha=0.2, color='blue')\n",
        "\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('Bond Maturity (years)', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('Bond Price (as % of par)', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')\n",
        "ax.set_title('Zero-Coupon Bond Prices (Dothan Model)\\nr₀=3%, μ=2%, σ=15%',\n",
        "             fontsize=13, fontweight='bold')\n",
        "ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
        "ax.set_ylim([0.6, 1.05])\n",
        "ax.axhline(y=1.0, color='red', linestyle='--', alpha=0.5, label='Par Value')\n",
        "ax.legend()\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.tight_layout()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "monte-carlo-bond-pricing",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
