      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Coupon-Bearing Bond Pricing\n",
        "\n",
        "### Extension to Coupon Bonds\n",
        "\n",
        "For a coupon-bearing bond paying coupons $C$ at times $t_1, t_2, \\ldots, t_n$ and face value $F$ at maturity:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$P(0, T) = E \\left[ \\sum_{i=1}^{n} \\frac{C}{(1 + r_{t_i})^{T_i}} + \\frac{F}{(1+r_T)^T} \\right]$$\n",
        "\n",
        "In Monte Carlo:\n",
        "\n",
        "```python\n",
        "def price_coupon_bond(r0, mu, sigma, T, coupon_rate, face_value, dt, n_paths):\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    Price a coupon-bearing bond\n",
        "    C = coupon_rate * face_value\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    discount_factors = np.zeros(n_paths)\n",
        "    coupon = coupon_rate * face_value\n",
        "    \n",
        "    for path in range(n_paths):\n",
        "        r = r0\n",
        "        pv = 0\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Discount all coupons and principal\n",
        "        for t in np.arange(0, T, coupon_freq):\n",
        "            r_next = r + mu * r * dt + sigma * r * np.sqrt(dt) * np.random.standard_normal()\n",
        "            discount = np.exp(-r * coupon_freq)\n",
        "            pv += coupon * discount\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Add principal\n",
        "        final_discount = np.exp(-r * T)\n",
        "        pv += face_value * final_discount\n",
        "        \n",
        "        discount_factors[path] = pv\n",
        "    \n",
        "    return np.mean(discount_factors)\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Duration and Convexity\n",
        "\n",
        "### Modified Duration\n",
        "\n",
        "The **modified duration** measures bond price sensitivity to small rate changes:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$D_{\\text{mod}} = -\\frac{1}{P} \\frac{dP}{dr}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For a bond, this is approximately:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\Delta P \\approx -D_{\\text{mod}} \\cdot P \\cdot \\Delta r$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Example: A bond with modified duration of 5 and price $100 will lose approximately $5 when rates rise by 1%.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Convexity\n",
        "\n",
        "Convexity accounts for the non-linearity:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\Delta P \\approx -D_{\\text{mod}} \\cdot P \\cdot \\Delta r + \\frac{1}{2} C \\cdot P \\cdot (\\Delta r)^2$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Long-duration bonds gain more when rates fall than they lose when rates rise equally.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Connecting Convexity to Stochastic Rates\n",
        "\n",
        "Under the Dothan model with high volatility, bonds exhibit **more convexity** because there's more uncertainty about future rates. This makes them more valuable (all else equal).\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Factors Affecting Bond Prices\n",
        "\n",
        "| Factor | Effect on Bond Price | Intuition |\n",
        "|--------|-----|-----------|\n",
        "| ↑ Interest rates | ↓ Price falls | Future cashflows are discounted more heavily |\n",
        "| ↑ Maturity | ↑↓ Mixed | Longer duration → more sensitive to rates |\n",
        "| ↑ Volatility (σ) | ↑ Price rises | Uncertainty increases value (convexity) |\n",
        "| ↑ Coupon | ↑ Price rises | More cashflow received earlier |\n",
        "| ↑ Credit risk | ↓ Price falls | Higher default probability |\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Practical Considerations\n",
        "\n",
        "### Convergence of Monte Carlo\n",
        "\n",
        "- **High variability** in small samples due to randomness\n",
        "- **Standard error** decreases as $1/\\sqrt{n_\\text{paths}}$\n",
        "- Rule of thumb: need 10,000–100,000 paths for 3–4 decimal place accuracy\n",
        "\n",
        "### Choice of Drift Parameter\n",
        "\n",
        "- For **risk-neutral pricing**: Use the risk-neutral drift (often 0 or calibrated from market prices)\n",
        "- For **real-world forecasting**: Use the actual drift estimated from data\n",
        "- This distinction is crucial: risk-neutral = pricing, real-world = forecasting\n",
        "\n",
        "### Discretization Error\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Euler scheme**: Error is $O(\\Delta t)$\n",
        "- **Smaller $\\Delta t$**: More accurate but slower\n",
        "- Typical choice: $\\Delta t = 0.01$ (10 steps per year × 10 years = 100 simulations per path)\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Summary\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Bond pricing** under stochastic rates is the expected present value across all possible rate paths\n",
        "- **Monte Carlo** provides a flexible computational method\n",
        "- **Dothan model** has both analytical solutions and works with simulation\n",
        "- **Duration and convexity** remain essential risk measures\n",
        "- **Volatility increases bond prices** due to convexity (optionality value)\n",
        "\n",
        "Next, let's implement the complete simulation and pricing workflow!"
      ],
      "id": "5bb81f0d"
    }
